–1386":"1305–1386","1298–1364":"1298–1364","1331–1382":"1331–1382","1305":"1305","1331":"1331","1364":"1364","1386":"1386","1298":"1298","1382":"1382","Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England","Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Yester, Haddingtonshire, Schotland","Dirleton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Dirleton, Haddingtonshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1305–1386":"1305–1386","1298–1364":"1298–1364","1331–1382":"1331–1382","1305":"1305","1331":"1331","1364":"1364","1386":"1386","1298":"1298","1382":"1382","Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England","Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Dirleton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Dirleton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Douglas","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from any of various places called from their situation on a river named with Gaelic <i>dubh</i> ‘dark, black’ + <i>glas</i> ‘stream’ (a derivative of <i>glas</i> ‘blue’). There are several localities in Scotland and Ireland so named, but the one from which the surname is derived in most if not all cases is Douglas in Lanarkshire 20 miles south of Glasgow, the original stronghold of the influential Douglas family and their retainers.","History: The family taking their name from Douglas in Lanarkshire were of Flemish origin. They rose to great prominence in the 14th and 15th centuries, controlling the earldoms of Douglas, Morton, and Angus, and later, Queensberry."],"variants":[{"name":"Douglass","meanings":["Scottish and English (Durham and Northumbria): variant of   Douglas  .","History: William Douglass, a physician recognized for his identification and description of an epidemic of scarlet fever, was born <i>c.</i> 1691 in Gifford, Haddington County, Scotland, and settled in Boston in 1718. The abolitionist, orator, and journalist Frederick Douglass assumed the name after escaping from slavery in 1838 and traveling to Massachusetts. Son of a white father and a slave with some Indian blood, he was born Frederick Augustus Washington Bailey <i>c.</i> 1817 in Tuckahoe, MD."]}]},{"name":"Catherine","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."],"variants":[{"name":"Catheryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Katherine","meanings":["Variant of   Katherine ."]},{"name":"Catharin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathryn","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Cathrin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]},{"name":"Catharine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Katherine .  This form of the name is also used in France."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Catherine Douglas was born in 1305. She had at least 1 daughter with William de Vaux - Lord of Direlton. She died in 1386, at the age of 81."},"et":{"1305–1386":"1305–1386","1298–1364":"1298–1364","1331–1382":"1331–1382","1305":"1305","1331":"1331","1364":"1364","1386":"1386","1298":"1298","1382":"1382","Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England","Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Yester, Haddingtonshire, Scotland","Dirleton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland":"Dirleton, Haddingtonshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1305–1386":"1305–1386","1298–1364":"1298–1364","1331–1382":"1331–1382","1305":"1305","1331":"1331","1364":"1364","1386":"1386","1298":"1298","1382":"1382","Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Cotham, Nottinghamshire, England","Yester, Haddin